Caption.String: The deliberate management of a wind plant to reduce the amount of energy compared to what is possible from the available resource.
Turbine performance losses represent the amount of energy that is not produced by a wind turbine at a given wind speed compared to the OEM power curve.
Electrical losses from a wind farm are the energy losses inherent in energy transmission in collector lines, transformers, and other site equipment and transmission to the point of revenue metering.

Internal Wake loss can be set as a constant percent loss on the Wind Farm page, under Wake Effects, by choosing the Constant Loss Wake Model. Otherwise Internal Wake Loss will be zero and will be calculated using the given Wake Model.
Energy-based availability is the amount of energy produced as a percentage of the total amount of energy that the wind plant could have captured if turbines were always ready to generate power.
Environmental losses account for performance degradation and shut downs due to environmental factors such as weather, ambient temperature, and tree growth.
